{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":4843,"record_hash":"sha256:68540dea1a644b7fcf3e658d87a821f2728c3de388d95fea71c572004fbe02d8","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:02:26.520Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"::code-comment{title=\"[P1] Object keys still bypass redaction\" body=\"High-entropy strings used as JSON object keys are copied unchanged, so an arbitrary map like `{ \\\"[REDACTED:entropy]\\\": true }` would store the token verbatim while reporting no key redaction. Since transcript/tool payloads can contain arbitrary JSON maps, key redaction is worth handling or explicitly scoping out.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=44 end=50 priority=1 confidence=0.88}\n\n::code-comment{title=\"[P1] UUID exemption can preserve UUID-plus-secret tokens\" body=\"`is_uuidish_identifier()` allows any alphanumeric/boundary affix up to 32 bytes around a UUID. That preserves useful `turn_id=<uuid>` shapes, but it also preserves opaque values like `[REDACTED:entropy]` in full. The allowlist should probably be narrowed to bare UUIDs or known label-plus-UUID forms.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=135 end=140 priority=1 confidence=0.82}\n\n::code-comment{title=\"[P2] Nearby Git labels can whitelist unrelated hex secrets\" body=\"A 40/64-hex candidate is preserved when any Git-ish label appears within a 32-byte window before or after it. In transcript prose or shell commands, words like `commit`, `sha`, or `object` can appear near unrelated tokens, for example `TOKEN=<40hex>; git commit -m fix`, causing a secret-shaped value to be treated as a Git object ID. A tighter immediate-label or exact-field rule would keep this POC small.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=208 end=212 priority=2 confidence=0.78}\n\nThe cleanup pass repeated the small P3 nits about `RedactedValue` and `is_obvious_non_secret`, but I’d leave those behind the behavior findings. Local checks still passed: `cargo test -p but-agentlog redaction --lib` and `cargo clippy -p but-agentlog --all-targets --no-deps`.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:02:26.520Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}